# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1888-philadelphia-athletics-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1888-philadelphia-athletics-season/1887-philadelphia-athletics-season] The **1887 Philadelphia Athletics** had a 64–69 record and finished in fifth place in the American Association.
[src:1888-philadelphia-athletics-season/1888-boston-beaneaters-season] The **1888 Boston Beaneaters season** was the 18th season of the franchise.
[src:1888-philadelphia-athletics-season/1888-brooklyn-bridegrooms-season] With the 1888 season, the Brooklyn Grays underwent a name change to the **Brooklyn Bridegrooms**, a nickname that resulted from several team members getting married around the same time.
[src:1888-philadelphia-athletics-season/1888-brooklyn-bridegrooms-season] Also, owner Charles Byrne decided to withdraw from managing the team's on field activities and turned the reins over to more experienced baseball manager Bill McGunnigle.
[src:1888-philadelphia-athletics-season/1888-brooklyn-bridegrooms-season] That, along with the Bridegrooms' purchase of several top players from the defunct New York Metropolitans, led to a dramatic on field improvement as the team finished in second place in the American Association.
[src:1888-philadelphia-athletics-season/1888-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1888 Chicago White Stockings season** was the 17th season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the 13th in the National League and the fourth at the first West Side Park.
[src:1888-philadelphia-athletics-season/1888-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished second in the National League with a record of 77–58, 9 games behind the New York Giants.
[src:1888-philadelphia-athletics-season/1888-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The **1888 Cincinnati Red Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1888-philadelphia-athletics-season/1888-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The team finished in fourth place in the American Association with a record of 80–54, 11.5 games behind the St.
[src:1888-philadelphia-athletics-season/1888-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati retained manager Gus Schmelz, who led the team to a franchise record 81 wins in 1887.
[src:1888-philadelphia-athletics-season/1888-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings were quiet during the off-season, as pitcher Lee Viau, who signed his first professional contract, was the only major signing by the team.
[src:1888-philadelphia-athletics-season/1888-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] John Reilly had the best season of his career, hitting .321 while leading the league with 13 home runs and 103 RBI, as he became the first Red Stocking to crack 100 RBI in a season.
[src:1888-philadelphia-athletics-season/1888-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Hugh Nicol hit only .239; however, he once again stole over 100 bases, finishing the season with 103.
[src:1888-philadelphia-athletics-season/1888-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Nicol and Reilly tied for the team high with 112 runs scored.
[src:1888-philadelphia-athletics-season/1888-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] On the mound, Lee Viau led Cincinnati with 27 wins and a 2.65 ERA in 42 starts.
[src:1888-philadelphia-athletics-season/1888-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Tony Mullane and Mike Smith each finished with over 20 wins as well, with 26 and 22 respectively.
[src:1888-philadelphia-athletics-season/1888-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings began the season red hot, as they had a 12–5 record before winning 10 games in a row to be 22–5, three games ahead of the second place St.
[src:1888-philadelphia-athletics-season/1888-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] Cincinnati then fell into a slump, going 5–16 in their next 21 games to fall into fourth place, seven games out of first.
[src:1888-philadelphia-athletics-season/1888-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] The Red Stockings remained in the pennant race until late in the season.
[src:1888-philadelphia-athletics-season/1888-cincinnati-red-stockings-season] However, the team finished the year in fourth place with an 80–54 record, 11.5 games behind the first place Browns.
[src:1888-philadelphia-athletics-season/1888-cleveland-blues-season] The **1888 Cleveland Blues** baseball team finished with a 50–82 record, sixth place in the American Association.
[src:1888-philadelphia-athletics-season/1888-philadelphia-athletics-season] The **1888 Philadelphia Athletics** finished with an 81–52 record and finished in third place in the American Association.
